            {'id': 'q10','question': "Rinsing your nose with saline solution can help wash out trapped PM2.5 particles.",'answer': True,'explanation': "**True!** Nasal rinsing is a good way to clean your nasal passages, washing out dust, allergens, and other irritants, which helps you breathe easier.",'infographic_key': 'nasal_rinse_benefits'},
            {'id': 'q11','question': "Applying petroleum jelly inside your nostrils can help trap PM2.5.",'answer': False,'explanation': "**False!** Applying petroleum jelly does not help trap dust and may cause skin irritation or clog pores.",'infographic_key': 'myth_busters'},
            {'id': 'q12','question': "If you can't see Doi Suthep clearly, it might mean the PM2.5 level is high that day.",'answer': True,'explanation': "**True!** Poor visibility is a key indicator that there is a high concentration of particulate matter in the air.",'infographic_key': 'visibility_guide'},
            {'id': 'q13','question': "Eating broccoli and fatty fish can help your body fight the effects of pollution.",'answer': True,'explanation': "**True!** Foods high in antioxidants (like sulforaphane in broccoli) and omega-3s (in fish) can help reduce inflammation in the body caused by pollutants.",'infographic_key': 'superfoods'},
            {'id': 'q14','question': "Our body can expel all the PM2.5 we breathe in.",'answer': False,'explanation': "**False!** While our body can trap larger particles, PM2.5 is so small it can bypass our defenses, reaching deep into the lungs and bloodstream, where it is difficult to remove and can accumulate over time.",'infographic_key': 'body_defense'},
